Here's the registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient → singleton so one instance manages connection pooling
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // DataService → singleton because it wraps HttpClient and holds
        // shared state (cache, auth tokens, etc.)
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels → transient so each navigation gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages → transient so each navigation creates a new page
        // bound to its own ViewModel instance
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | Singleton | One instance reuses TCP connections efficiently; avoids socket exhaustion |
| `IDataService` | Singleton | Shared API layer — caches, auth headers, and state live for the app's lifetime |
| ViewModels | Transient | Each navigation should get a clean ViewModel with fresh data, avoiding stale state |
| Pages | Transient | Pages hold UI state; fresh instances prevent visual artifacts from previous navigation |

**Key rules of thumb:**
- **Singleton** → stateless infrastructure or intentionally shared state (services, HTTP clients)
- **Transient** → anything tied to a user interaction or navigation (pages, ViewModels)
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET); avoid unless you create custom scopes

Pages receive their ViewModel via constructor injection:

```csharp
public partial class DetailPage : ContentPage
{
    public DetailPage(DetailViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

This way the DI container wires everything automatically — each page gets its own ViewModel, and all ViewModels share the same `DataService`.
